commentText: My own experience is as follows. I lived in NY for 26 yrs. Everybody knows how over crowded it is and the crowd is not exactly pleasant. The winters have been BRUTAL, if you drive you will be miserable. I got married and moved into 2 bedroom apartment paying $1425 per month. The second room was the size of a walk in closet. My wife and I made a combined $75k per yr. before taxes. After taxes we were making $52000. We had car payment, ins, utility bills, food, misc. etc. and were managing to save almost $1k per month. I have an ear condition that got progressively worse and the cold weather made it more acute. Combining my health condition and the STRESS of living in NY, I honestly felt that I was going crazy. My quality of life was ZERO. I decided to move to central Florida and my wife and I got jobs with the dept. of Education. It is not the best but we make a combined $3900 per month after taxes. We are currently renting a 4 bedroom 3 bathroom house with beautiful scenery and peaceful environment for $1250, We still pay car, ins, utilities, food, misc, etc. We manage to save the same about 1k per month. We are already planning on purchasing a home. Would I have been able to consider that in NY? NO.  In order for a married couple to purchase a home, they have to make a combined 150k and the house will not compare with what you can get in florida for just 200k. With that said, the quality of life cannot compare to NY. I feel alive here. In NY? dying slowly. I'm not saying that there are pros and cons and that everything has a catch but that is my honest experience so far.
